WEBVTT

00:05.353 --> 00:08.791
Tonight,
global business tycoon
Peter Jones joins the Tank.

00:08.834 --> 00:12.012
Peter is the most seasoned
investor on "Dragons' Den,"

00:12.055 --> 00:13.665
the U.K. version
of "Shark Tank,"

00:13.709 --> 00:15.667
with 18 seasons under his belt.

00:15.711 --> 00:17.278
I can help
you scale this business

00:17.321 --> 00:18.757
from a global perspective.

00:18.801 --> 00:19.976
That's what I bring
to the party.

00:20.020 --> 00:22.544
The British are coming!

00:22.587 --> 00:24.633
Ocean plastics are one of
the biggest

00:24.676 --> 00:26.983
environmental challenges
of our generation.

00:27.027 --> 00:28.332
We have got
the meals for busy people

00:28.376 --> 00:30.334
who care about
what they put in their bodies.

00:30.378 --> 00:32.075
It's a perfect tool
when you're multitasking

00:32.119 --> 00:33.424
or when you have a coworker
like Mr. Wonderful

00:33.468 --> 00:34.599
who keeps on ranting.

00:36.601 --> 00:38.081
This is
a lifelong dream realized,

00:38.125 --> 00:40.518
to be able to put my passion
for music into my career.

00:40.562 --> 00:41.824
I could be your perfect partner,

00:41.867 --> 00:43.391
and that's why I'm gonna
make you an offer.

00:43.434 --> 00:45.001
I know how to make
this thing huge.

00:45.045 --> 00:46.655
I'm afraid you guys
might hold me back.

00:46.698 --> 00:48.048
Who's ready
to take the bait?

00:48.091 --> 00:50.354
- It's a no-brainer.
- It's time
to make some money.

00:58.797 --> 01:00.060
First in the Tank

01:00.103 --> 01:02.758
is a way to give
the most memorable gift.

01:10.896 --> 01:12.550
Hi, Sharks.
I'm Ellen Hodges.

01:12.594 --> 01:14.030
And I'm Omayya Atout,

01:14.074 --> 01:17.120
and we're seeking $400,000
in exchange for 10% equity

01:17.164 --> 01:18.252
in Songlorious.

01:18.295 --> 01:20.819
Do you want to give a gift
that you know

01:20.863 --> 01:22.386
will get
a strong emotional reaction,

01:22.430 --> 01:27.087
a gift that captures memories,
a gift that creates new ones?

01:27.130 --> 01:29.089
Greeting cards, flowers,
they all fall flat

01:29.132 --> 01:30.612
'cause they're
kind of impersonal

01:30.655 --> 01:32.962
and, sooner or later,
and up in the trash.

01:34.616 --> 01:36.531
That's where
Songlorious comes in,

01:36.574 --> 01:39.142
with a gift
that lasts forever.

01:39.186 --> 01:41.492
Songlorious is a website
that anyone can use

01:41.536 --> 01:43.799
to have a personalized,
studio-quality song

01:43.842 --> 01:46.584
made completely from scratch
for any occasion.

01:46.628 --> 01:48.151
All you have to do
is go to the website,

01:48.195 --> 01:50.153
choose a genre,
tell us your story,

01:50.197 --> 01:51.676
and one of our artists
will have a song created

01:51.720 --> 01:52.721
especially for
your loved one.

01:52.764 --> 01:54.157
Let us give you
a little taste

01:54.201 --> 01:55.985
of what you could expect
from Songlorious.

02:43.119 --> 02:44.294
- - Yeah!
- - Very good.

02:44.338 --> 02:45.643
Yay!

02:45.687 --> 02:47.297
- Alright.
- Good job.

02:47.341 --> 02:49.473
So, Sharks, which one of you
wants to rock...

02:49.517 --> 02:50.822
And roll with us...

02:50.866 --> 02:52.389
Into the future
of gift giving?!

02:53.869 --> 02:54.913
- - Alright.
- - Good job.

02:54.957 --> 02:56.350
How does it work?

02:56.393 --> 02:58.787
So, every song is completely
unique and made per order.

02:58.830 --> 03:01.093
So, you go to the website,
you choose a genre,

03:01.137 --> 03:02.747
you tell us how long
you want the song to be.

03:02.791 --> 03:05.054
We've got options from
30 seconds to three minutes.

03:05.097 --> 03:08.231
And, you know, the price depends
on those two factors.

03:08.275 --> 03:09.667
And then you just
tell us your story.

03:09.711 --> 03:12.017
You tell us the occasion
and about the person it's for.

03:12.061 --> 03:14.237
Part of the order process,
you choose the genre,

03:14.281 --> 03:16.021
And some of them
are acoustic genres,

03:16.065 --> 03:17.153
which are priced
a little cheaper,

03:17.197 --> 03:18.328
and some of them
are full production.

03:18.372 --> 03:20.852
We've got pop-rock,
country-rock, EDM.

03:20.896 --> 03:22.245
And then
it's up to the artists

03:22.289 --> 03:23.855
to provide
all of the instrumentation.

03:23.899 --> 03:25.509
What's the price between
a 30-second

03:25.553 --> 03:26.902
versus a three-minute?

03:26.945 --> 03:28.991
So, a 30-second is $45.

03:29.034 --> 03:31.515
That's what it starts at
for an acoustic song

03:31.559 --> 03:33.561
And for a full
three-minute song,

03:33.604 --> 03:36.303
if it's acoustic, $205.

03:36.346 --> 03:40.524
And if it's a full
instrumentation, it's $230.

03:40.568 --> 03:41.786
So, how does it work, then?

03:41.830 --> 03:43.614
So you've got a load
of freelance singers?

03:43.658 --> 03:44.963
Yes.
Yes.

03:45.007 --> 03:47.096
We have about 100 musicians
on our team right now.

03:47.139 --> 03:49.185
And how much do you pay them
each time they do a song?

03:49.229 --> 03:51.709
So we pay them anywhere
between 35% to 55%

03:51.753 --> 03:53.189
of the song's order cost,

03:53.233 --> 03:55.844
plus any tips that they get,
they get 100% of.

03:55.887 --> 03:58.238
And the average tip
is about $51.

03:58.281 --> 03:59.717
- Wow.
- Good for them.
That's awesome.

03:59.761 --> 04:02.067
What have your sales been so far
since you've launched?

04:02.111 --> 04:05.201
So last year
we made $700,000.

04:05.245 --> 04:06.637
- Oh!
- Wow.

04:06.681 --> 04:08.639
This year to date,
we've made $1.1 million.

04:08.683 --> 04:10.032
Wow.
That's so great.
Whoa!

04:10.075 --> 04:11.120
O'You made $1.1 million.

04:11.163 --> 04:12.600
What do you get
to the bottom line

04:12.643 --> 04:13.688
by the time bottom line
by the time...?

04:13.731 --> 04:15.255
The bottom line
is 9% profit so far.

04:15.298 --> 04:17.474
- 9%?
- And that's after you guys
pay yourselves, obviously.

04:17.518 --> 04:18.823
No, that's before
we pay ourselves.

04:18.867 --> 04:19.607
Ohh.

04:19.650 --> 04:21.043
Well,
when we started,

04:21.086 --> 04:22.392
we were living
in Brooklyn

04:22.436 --> 04:24.307
in an apartment
with four other roommates,

04:24.351 --> 04:26.353
and I just basically used
my personal credit cards

04:26.396 --> 04:28.050
to start the website.

04:28.093 --> 04:30.270
And basically
any money we were making,

04:30.313 --> 04:31.314
we were putting back in.

04:31.358 --> 04:32.707
How did you come
up with this idea?

04:32.750 --> 04:34.535
So, we're both musicians.

04:34.578 --> 04:36.145
We made
a personalized song

04:36.188 --> 04:38.060
for one of my friends
for their wedding

04:38.103 --> 04:39.888
right before
the pandemic hit,

04:39.931 --> 04:42.934
and then we decided to kind of
turn that idea into a website

04:42.978 --> 04:44.327
and make the songs ourself.

04:44.371 --> 04:45.807
We hoped to do
about three songs a week

04:45.850 --> 04:47.765
just for fun
and some extra money.

04:47.809 --> 04:49.898
And then put some
advertising money behind it

04:49.941 --> 04:51.856
because we believed
in the idea.

04:51.900 --> 04:53.771
But then we started getting more
orders than we could handle.

04:53.815 --> 04:57.122
We were staying up all night
in our apartment, making music.

04:57.166 --> 04:58.907
- Writing music, too.
- And we were overwhelmed.

04:58.950 --> 05:00.604
And that's
at the same time

05:00.648 --> 05:02.389
artists were contacting us,
like,

05:02.432 --> 05:04.826
"Hey, we saw your ad.
I'm looking for work."

05:04.869 --> 05:07.045
And we were like, "Join the team
'cause we need people."

05:07.089 --> 05:09.047
This is a lifelong dream
realized, to be able

05:09.091 --> 05:11.746
to put my passion
for music into my career.

05:11.789 --> 05:13.356
It's the best feeling
in the world.

05:13.400 --> 05:15.140
And to do it with, you know,
the love of my life.

05:15.184 --> 05:16.577
Now, who has knocked you off
so far?

05:16.620 --> 05:17.969
How many competitors
do you have?

05:18.013 --> 05:19.623
So, there are other businesses
that do this.

05:19.667 --> 05:21.451
You know, personalized
songs have really been around

05:21.495 --> 05:23.018
since the singing telegram.

05:23.061 --> 05:25.890
It's not -- it seems new,
but it's very old.

05:25.934 --> 05:28.545
There are some websites out
there that are just one person.

05:28.589 --> 05:31.461
They typically have
long turnaround times
and high prices.

05:31.505 --> 05:33.507
And then the other ones
that have a roster of musicians

05:33.550 --> 05:35.204
are typically
templated songs

05:35.247 --> 05:37.249
where they just change a name,
and, you know...

05:37.293 --> 05:39.556
Is it just the two of you
running the company?

05:39.600 --> 05:40.818
It started
just the two of us.

05:40.862 --> 05:42.646
Now we have four
full-time employees.

05:42.690 --> 05:44.692
So, where do you see
this company going?

05:44.735 --> 05:47.564
We can copy and paste
this model into other languages.

05:47.608 --> 05:49.305
Right now we only do songs
in English.

05:49.349 --> 05:51.568
We really want to dive into
the wedding sector as well.

05:51.612 --> 05:53.570
We do a lot of songs
for weddings already,

05:53.614 --> 05:55.964
but we feel like there's
a lot of opportunity there.

05:56.007 --> 05:57.269
Wedding sector.

05:57.313 --> 05:59.881
And then additionally,
with the corporate world,

05:59.924 --> 06:01.839
you know, we already
have a couple of companies

06:01.883 --> 06:03.188
who are ordering songs
all the time.

06:03.232 --> 06:04.842
Anytime somebody
gets promoted or hired,

06:04.886 --> 06:06.148
they buy them a custom song.

06:06.191 --> 06:07.758
What would you like
to use the money for?

06:07.802 --> 06:10.848
We're going to use it
for all the marketing expansions

06:10.892 --> 06:12.676
that we're looking for,
whether it's digital, you know,

06:12.720 --> 06:14.286
television, radio, et cetera.

06:14.330 --> 06:16.158
The truth is, you know,
we're musicians,

06:16.201 --> 06:17.768
we're not
marketing experts.

06:17.812 --> 06:19.509
We've come this far,
but we really need --

06:19.553 --> 06:20.945
You want to use
the $400,000

06:20.989 --> 06:22.425
to professionalize
the whole operation, basically.

06:22.469 --> 06:23.557
Exactly.
Exactly.

06:23.600 --> 06:25.472
I get the feeling
and sense that

06:25.515 --> 06:26.647
you're not businesspeople.

06:26.690 --> 06:28.083
That's why you're here.
You need help.

06:28.126 --> 06:29.693
Kevin.
Do you like this?

06:30.781 --> 06:32.130
- So do I.
- But do you have a forecast?

06:32.174 --> 06:34.350
Do you have any idea
of where this could get to?

06:34.394 --> 06:36.439
We have a general idea
from just forecasting

06:36.483 --> 06:37.658
regular numbers-wise.

06:37.701 --> 06:39.703
We're looking at
$2.5 million this year,

06:39.747 --> 06:41.401
and we're looking out
for about

06:41.444 --> 06:42.576
$5 million next year.

06:42.619 --> 06:44.534
So, in the U.K.,
I used to own a company

06:44.578 --> 06:45.709
called Red Letter Days.

06:45.753 --> 06:47.494
Basically, it was
an experience company.

06:47.537 --> 06:49.974
You could buy a recording
for whatever you wanted,

06:50.018 --> 06:51.411
for a birthday,
for whatever.

06:51.454 --> 06:52.629
Very, very similar.

06:52.673 --> 06:54.762
We sold it,
and we made a lot of money.

06:54.805 --> 06:57.373
One thing that was really
interesting is it took off.

06:57.417 --> 06:58.548
Yeah.
Yeah.

06:58.592 --> 07:00.332
It was really, really big.

07:00.376 --> 07:01.725
But it took off
because we decided

07:01.769 --> 07:03.205
to make it really simple.

07:03.248 --> 07:03.814
Mm-hmm.

07:03.858 --> 07:05.120
And your website

07:05.163 --> 07:06.861
and your technology
you're using

07:06.904 --> 07:08.993
is absolutely vital
to get that right.

07:09.037 --> 07:12.475
But I do think, with the right
backup in terms of technology,

07:12.519 --> 07:15.478
I think this could be huge,
particularly for weddings.

07:15.522 --> 07:17.132
That means so much
- to hear it from you.
- Thank you.

07:17.175 --> 07:18.568
Guys, with what's happening

07:18.612 --> 07:21.484
in artificial intelligence,
you've seen, you know,

07:21.528 --> 07:24.269
emulated voices that sound
really, really, really good.

07:24.313 --> 07:25.314
Mm-hmm.

07:25.357 --> 07:26.968
I have a company
called Synthesia,

07:27.011 --> 07:28.752
and that's all they do
is replicate voices.

07:28.796 --> 07:31.102
- Wow.
- So you can take my voice

07:31.146 --> 07:33.496
saying this and convert it
to 30 different languages.

07:33.540 --> 07:34.889
Ellen, Omayya,

07:34.932 --> 07:36.543
based on this experience
that I have

07:36.586 --> 07:38.066
in growing businesses like this,

07:38.109 --> 07:40.068
I could be
your perfect partner.

07:40.111 --> 07:41.504
And that's why I'm gonna
make you an offer.

07:41.548 --> 07:42.897
- Okay.
- Oh!

07:42.940 --> 07:45.769
But my offer
doesn't come cheap.

07:45.813 --> 07:48.424
I'm going to
offer you $400,000,

07:48.468 --> 07:51.166
but I'd like to share
the business with you equally,

07:51.209 --> 07:52.950
I'd like a third
of the business.

07:52.994 --> 07:54.517
- Oh!
- We appreciate the offer
very much.

07:54.561 --> 07:55.649
Yeah.
Thank you.

07:55.692 --> 07:57.999
This type of business
could be huge.

07:58.042 --> 08:00.044
I can help you scale
this business

08:00.088 --> 08:01.872
from a global perspective,
and I think that's

08:01.916 --> 08:03.831
really important
for a business like this.

08:03.874 --> 08:06.311
Absolutely.
The global market is definitely
something we're interested in.

08:06.355 --> 08:09.358
I think Peter has a great offer
on the table.

08:09.401 --> 08:13.710
That's why I'll match that,
but for 20%.

08:13.754 --> 08:14.755
Wow.
Appreciate the offer.

08:26.897 --> 08:28.116
All sharks are still in.

08:28.159 --> 08:30.727
Ellen and Omayya have two offers
on the table

08:30.771 --> 08:33.556
for their custom song business,
Songlorious.

08:33.600 --> 08:35.776
But Mark and Kevin
may also be interested.

08:35.819 --> 08:38.561
I'm huge in the wedding
industry, obviously,

08:38.605 --> 08:41.999
but I like Cuban's
technology idea,

08:42.043 --> 08:44.045
and he owns that company
that has a piece of it.

08:44.088 --> 08:47.570
How about we partner,
Cuban and I, 50/50,

08:47.614 --> 08:49.006
offer you the $400,000?

08:49.050 --> 08:50.573
We'll do it for 25%.

08:53.445 --> 08:55.317
Actually, what we should
do is we should see

08:55.360 --> 08:58.059
if Peter wants to come in
and go to the 33%,

08:58.102 --> 09:00.452
but let Peter handle
the international,

09:00.496 --> 09:03.238
Kevin handle the weddings
and everything.

09:03.281 --> 09:05.240
I can deal with
the technological side.

09:05.283 --> 09:07.111
Now, we'd still need the 33%.

09:07.155 --> 09:08.765
That gives us enough each
to care.

09:08.809 --> 09:09.810
If Peter's
in for that.

09:09.853 --> 09:12.203
I would love to do that.

09:12.247 --> 09:14.554
Come on, guys,
give me some room here.

09:14.597 --> 09:16.468
Hey, why don't we
take it up to 40%?

09:16.512 --> 09:17.644
I'm gonna add the diversity.

09:17.687 --> 09:19.210
No.

09:19.254 --> 09:20.429
You know how close I am
with the music community.

09:20.472 --> 09:22.039
Come on, man.

09:22.083 --> 09:23.780
Wait, listen, this is gonna be
a social-media play, right?

09:23.824 --> 09:25.434
African-Americans,
we like to talk.

09:25.477 --> 09:28.176
So, why don't you let me in
on it a little bit?

09:28.219 --> 09:29.743
- Give me a little sidewalk here.
- O'Daymond, Daymond.

09:29.786 --> 09:31.005
Another 7%,
we all split it.

09:31.048 --> 09:32.484
