And is it just the two
of you running the company?

34:25.193 --> 34:27.326
Like, tell me
how is this operation being run.

34:27.369 --> 34:28.718
It's the two of us.

34:28.762 --> 34:32.200
I mean, it's bootstrapped,
nose to the grindstone,

34:32.244 --> 34:33.332
pounding down doors.

34:33.375 --> 34:34.550
You're doing everything,
though?

34:34.594 --> 34:36.117
Mike likes to tell stories,
doesn't he?

34:36.161 --> 34:37.771
- Mike's a storyteller, right?
- I'll jump in.

34:37.814 --> 34:39.773
He's Italian,
I'm Italian.

34:39.816 --> 34:41.601
If we're not talking,
we don't know what to do.

34:41.644 --> 34:44.734
But it's very much
an all-hands-on-deck
kind of effort.

34:44.778 --> 34:47.128
And are you 50/50 partners?

34:47.172 --> 34:49.565
No. Right now I own 100%
of the company.

34:49.609 --> 34:51.089
Michael.
You do?

34:51.132 --> 34:52.960
I do.
- He does.
- And what about Lauren?

34:53.003 --> 34:54.744
I still have
a full-time job

34:54.788 --> 34:56.006
and I'm working
on Long Wharf

34:56.050 --> 34:57.617
mornings, nights,
and weekends right now.

34:57.660 --> 34:59.619
Well, why doesn't Lauren
have a percentage?

34:59.662 --> 35:01.316
Yeah, why doesn't
Lauren have a percentage?

35:01.360 --> 35:04.754
There's a couple negotiations
we can do in this room today.

35:04.798 --> 35:06.626
Hey, who's the Shark?

35:06.669 --> 35:08.149
Hang on, Mike.
Just give me one second here.

35:08.193 --> 35:09.759
$375,000, 15%.

35:09.803 --> 35:12.197
$2.5 million valuation.

35:12.240 --> 35:14.677
$495,000 in sales.

35:14.721 --> 35:16.636
I get the oyster story.
That's really great.

35:16.679 --> 35:18.159
But it's a sweater business,
okay?

35:18.203 --> 35:20.466
Your worth
is sort of one-time sales.

35:20.509 --> 35:22.859
$375,000 --

35:22.903 --> 35:26.341
I'd need to have like
75% of it.

35:26.385 --> 35:28.300
We appreciate the offer,

35:28.343 --> 35:30.215
I haven't said ...but that deal's a little
too steep for us.

35:31.607 --> 35:33.131
He didn't
give an offer.

35:33.174 --> 35:35.263
O'
Mike, let me tell you --
the valuation's insane.

35:35.307 --> 35:37.831
The company's not even worth
$375,000 yet.

35:37.874 --> 35:39.224
You asked for too much money.

35:39.267 --> 35:41.182
I'm out.

35:41.226 --> 35:44.185
We appreciate it, Mr. Wonderful.
Thank you for your time.

35:44.229 --> 35:46.013
You know, I mean,
I'm really attracted to this

35:46.056 --> 35:49.016
because my daughter
is five years old.

35:49.059 --> 35:50.887
You know, they asked
all the kids in school,

35:50.931 --> 35:52.976
"What do you want to be?"
and two of the kids say,

35:53.020 --> 35:54.804
"I want to be a venture
capitalist when I get older."

35:54.848 --> 35:57.242
My daughter said,
"I want to pick up trash."

35:57.285 --> 35:58.721
Interesting.

35:58.765 --> 36:00.636
Nothing against
the hardworking men and women

36:00.680 --> 36:02.116
that clean up our cities.

36:02.160 --> 36:03.987
And I asked her, "Why do you
want to pick up trash?"

36:04.031 --> 36:05.772
And then she looked at me
at five years old

36:05.815 --> 36:07.904
with those big, beautiful eyes
and said,

36:07.948 --> 36:09.819
"Because I want to clean up
the world, Daddy."

36:09.863 --> 36:11.169
Right?
- Ohh.
- Aww.

36:11.212 --> 36:13.475
And so this
is something I want to do.

36:13.519 --> 36:16.826
It's something that
our kids need to understand.

36:16.870 --> 36:21.004
But the number is so much
to wrap our heads around,

36:21.048 --> 36:24.051
and I would be making
an uneducated decision

36:24.094 --> 36:26.009
and paying the most
I could for it.

36:26.053 --> 36:27.620
So we're trying to --So I have to pass.
I'm out.

36:27.663 --> 36:28.925
With that $375,000 --

36:28.969 --> 36:30.884
Oh, we appreciate
your time, Daymond.

36:30.927 --> 36:33.147
Um, I think
it's really interesting.

36:33.191 --> 36:35.889
You do think that there's a gap
in the market, don't you?

36:35.932 --> 36:37.238
We do.
I mean, we see ourselves

36:37.282 --> 36:40.546
becoming the face
of the circular economy.

36:40.589 --> 36:42.461
We believe that --That wasn't an opportunity
for a speech.

36:42.504 --> 36:44.027
It was just a statement.

36:44.071 --> 36:45.290
No, I'm just --

36:45.333 --> 36:47.553
What I'm looking at now is,

36:47.596 --> 36:49.990
is there actually
a market in that gap?

36:50.033 --> 36:52.122
Because I think
what your mission

36:52.166 --> 36:53.994
and what you're trying
to stand for is really great.

36:54.037 --> 36:55.778
How do you make this
into a business?

36:55.822 --> 36:58.390
Isn't there something bigger
that you could be doing

36:58.433 --> 37:00.914
that would be helping the oceans
in an even bigger way

37:00.957 --> 37:02.350
You don't like this business
at all?

37:02.394 --> 37:03.960
- No.
We'd like to get there,

37:04.004 --> 37:06.224
and I think we're on the track
to do that.

37:06.267 --> 37:07.660
Let me ask the question
a different way.

37:07.703 --> 37:10.140
Can you sell something
that everybody can afford to buy

37:10.184 --> 37:11.794
so everybody can participate,

37:11.838 --> 37:14.057
a T-shirt
that everybody can say,

37:14.101 --> 37:16.234
"Hey,
I'm supporting conservation

37:16.277 --> 37:20.063
and reclamation of oysters
and making the oceans better"?

37:20.107 --> 37:22.544
There's got to be
a path to scale.

37:22.588 --> 37:24.242
Yes, and there is.

37:24.285 --> 37:26.592
So, right now what we've been
talking to you guys about

37:26.635 --> 37:28.724
is our lambswool blend.

37:28.768 --> 37:30.857
But something that we're
working on

37:30.900 --> 37:33.207
is a cotton
and recycled-material blend.

37:33.251 --> 37:35.905
It's much more versatile
than our wool blend,

37:35.949 --> 37:38.299
which is made
to keep you warm.

37:38.343 --> 37:41.650
Just tell me, can you sell
a T-shirt for $29.95,

37:41.694 --> 37:44.218
make 60-plus percent margins,

37:44.262 --> 37:47.395
accomplish the same thing,
and sell five million of them?

37:47.439 --> 37:49.310
We think we can sell
five million of these sweaters.

37:49.354 --> 37:50.268
I'm out.

37:53.183 --> 37:55.055
We do appreciate
your time.

37:55.098 --> 37:56.491
You know what's a bummer?

37:56.535 --> 37:59.625
Mark's idea's a really great one
because people care.

37:59.668 --> 38:01.801
His daughter cares.
We all care, right?

38:01.844 --> 38:04.020
And we want to be able to
do things and get behind things,

38:04.064 --> 38:05.326
but, to Mark's point,

38:05.370 --> 38:08.634
in an affordable,
inexpensive way, a T-shirt.

38:08.677 --> 38:11.593
And when he said,
"How about doing that?
Can you tell me doing that?"

38:11.637 --> 38:12.942
And if you had said to him,
"Yes,"

38:12.986 --> 38:14.335
I would have said,
"Mark, I want to join you."

38:14.379 --> 38:16.337
But you didn't.

38:16.381 --> 38:17.904
- Look at Michael.
- - But you didn't.

38:17.947 --> 38:19.819
It was the moment
to jump in and say,

38:19.862 --> 38:22.343
"Yeah, you know what? It's a
good idea. We'll figure it out."

38:22.387 --> 38:24.258
We'll make anything
- out of oyster shells.
- And you guys, unfortunately,

38:24.302 --> 38:25.738
Now you're talking, but......because you didn't,

38:25.781 --> 38:27.870
I'm so sorry,
but I'm out.

38:29.524 --> 38:31.265
- Well, we appreciate it, Lori.
- Thank you for your time, Lori.

38:31.309 --> 38:33.572
Look, I think you've come
with a great product,

38:33.615 --> 38:35.661
a really, really good idea.

38:35.704 --> 38:38.054
There's two things
I don't like about it.

38:38.098 --> 38:39.969
One is clearly the valuation.

38:40.013 --> 38:41.884
And the second thing,
interestingly,

38:41.928 --> 38:44.017
is you haven't given any share
to your sister,

38:44.060 --> 38:45.671
who I think is
just about as passionate

38:45.714 --> 38:47.412
in this business as you are.

38:47.455 --> 38:49.718
So can you answer
why that hasn't happened?

38:49.762 --> 38:53.374
Honestly, Peter, we haven't
even thought about it yet.

38:53.418 --> 38:55.333
Lauren's put in
the time.

38:55.376 --> 38:56.682
Did you think about, Lauren?

38:56.725 --> 38:58.074
You might want to ask
Lauren that, yeah.

38:58.118 --> 39:00.294
Lauren, would you take it
if he offered you equity?

39:00.338 --> 39:01.643
Yeah, absolutely.

39:01.687 --> 39:03.253
Michael, are you going to
offer her some equity?

39:03.297 --> 39:04.603
Yes.

39:04.646 --> 39:05.952
How much
is she gonna get?

39:07.388 --> 39:08.737
I'd like to see
Michael's commitment.

39:08.781 --> 39:10.304
How much
would you give her now?

39:10.348 --> 39:11.436
Hmm.

39:11.479 --> 39:12.915
Lauren, what do you want?

39:12.959 --> 39:13.916
I'll take 10%.

39:13.960 --> 39:14.700
That's it?

39:14.743 --> 39:15.831
Done.

39:15.875 --> 39:17.267
Alright!
We got a deal finally.

39:17.311 --> 39:18.965
Great, you've just done a deal
in the Shark Tank.

39:19.008 --> 39:20.619
- Congratulations.
- We'll take it.

39:20.662 --> 39:22.838
You might do another one 'cause
I'm gonna make you an offer.

39:22.882 --> 39:25.058
Awesome.
Let's hear it.

39:25.101 --> 39:28.278
I am able
to help you sell this

39:28.322 --> 39:31.804
on a global basis
in multiple markets.

39:31.847 --> 39:33.936
I've got a business --
I'm a major shareholder.

39:33.980 --> 39:35.416
It's called Localised.

39:35.460 --> 39:37.766
We take even American brands,

39:37.810 --> 39:39.942
and we put them
into global markets.

39:39.986 --> 39:41.248
I'm going to offer you
all of the money --

39:41.291 --> 39:44.512
that's $375,000 --

39:44.556 --> 39:46.949
but I want 45%
- of the business.
- Ooh!

39:46.993 --> 39:48.124
- O'- Yowza!
- - Wow.

39:48.168 --> 39:49.387
Wow!

39:59.309 --> 40:00.572
Four Sharks are out.

40:00.615 --> 40:02.748
Peter is interested
in Lauren and Mike's

40:02.791 --> 40:05.272
recycled-oyster sweater company,
Long Wharf,

40:05.315 --> 40:06.708
but he wants a much bigger bite

40:06.752 --> 40:09.015
than the 15%
they came in offering.

40:09.058 --> 40:10.320
I'm going to offer you
all of the money --

40:10.364 --> 40:11.887
that's $375,000 --

40:11.931 --> 40:14.586
but I want 45%
- of the business.
- Ooh!

40:14.629 --> 40:15.369
- O'- Yowza!
- - Wow.

40:15.413 --> 40:16.370
Wow!

40:16.414 --> 40:17.719
The British are coming!

40:17.763 --> 40:20.156
Yeah. No...

40:20.200 --> 40:22.202
That they are.
Um...

40:22.245 --> 40:23.769
I think that's
a hell of an offer

40:23.812 --> 40:25.901
because you don't
have anything yet.

40:25.945 --> 40:27.816
You got oysters,
you got some water bottles,

40:27.860 --> 40:29.165
you got nothing in sales.

40:29.209 --> 40:30.471
And you got
a new partner.

40:30.515 --> 40:33.735
You do that deal,
you lost 55% in one minute.

40:34.954 --> 40:36.521
Um...

40:36.564 --> 40:37.826
What are you thinking?

40:37.870 --> 40:40.046
Your dream for having
this business successful

40:40.089 --> 40:42.222
becomes reality
the minute you say yes.

40:42.265 --> 40:44.703
What do you
want to do?

40:49.838 --> 40:52.406
Yeah.

40:52.450 --> 40:55.453
Peter, we we'd love to have you
join the family.

40:55.496 --> 40:56.541
Great.

40:56.584 --> 40:58.412
We appreciate the offer,
but --

40:58.456 --> 41:00.240
Is that a deal?

41:00.283 --> 41:02.372
Would you consider 25%?

41:02.416 --> 41:03.199
- No.
- O'

41:04.549 --> 41:06.986
To Kevin's point, this business
today is worth

41:07.029 --> 41:08.988
maybe $300,000 to $500,000.

41:09.031 --> 41:10.511
That's the reality.

41:10.555 --> 41:14.254
And my business, we're the
only company in the world --

41:14.297 --> 41:16.517
this is a big statement,
but it's true --

41:16.561 --> 41:20.129
the only company in the world
that could take a global brand

41:20.173 --> 41:22.654
and open them up in
a localized market like Japan,

41:22.697 --> 41:26.005
Korea, and Asia
in 30 days or less.

41:26.048 --> 41:28.573
That makes a very,
very unique difference,

41:28.616 --> 41:30.096
and that's what I bring
to the party.

41:30.139 --> 41:33.752
There -- There's no
coming off of 45%?

41:33.795 --> 41:36.537
No, because I just feel
that there's gonna be
a lot of work here.

41:36.581 --> 41:40.193
I'm not gonna budge on that.
It's my final offer, so...

41:43.544 --> 41:44.763
Mm-hmm.

41:47.461 --> 41:51.204
Well, Lauren's made
the decision on this one.

41:51.247 --> 41:53.641
Peter, we really appreciate
your offer,

41:53.685 --> 41:55.600
but it's more than we're willing
to give up right now.

41:55.643 --> 41:57.689
Whoa!
Good for you guys.

41:57.732 --> 41:59.168
- Understandable.
- O'Are you kidding?

41:59.212 --> 42:00.605
No, that's smart as hell.

42:00.648 --> 42:02.737
We really appreciate everyone's
advice and time today.

42:02.781 --> 42:04.173
Good luck.

42:04.217 --> 42:06.262
Well, listen, Peter just got you
10% of the company.

42:06.306 --> 42:07.350
- That's true.
- Right?

42:07.394 --> 42:08.613
We're walking away
as winners.

42:08.656 --> 42:10.049
You've done a deal!
Well done.

42:10.092 --> 42:11.877
Absolutely.
Thanks, guys.

42:11.920 --> 42:13.618
Thanks, everyone.
- We appreciate your time.
- Good luck, guys.

42:13.661 --> 42:14.662
Congrats, guys.
Good luck.

42:14.706 --> 42:15.924
- - Good work.
- O'- Wow.

42:18.666 --> 42:20.146
So...

42:20.189 --> 42:22.583
- Look at you!
- Got one deal done.

42:22.627 --> 42:25.194
45% was way too high.

42:25.238 --> 42:27.762
I did give up 10% today
to a great partner

42:27.806 --> 42:29.590
who's been there
since the beginning,

42:29.634 --> 42:31.331
but we're still keeping it
in the family.
